body:
This wasn't very pleasant to dig through but I think I know _what_ is happening, but not the _why_. I abandoned the Qt notion here to see if I could reproduce the unresponsive window via a Win32 window being made then passing the handle to SFML. Used some source from [here](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/learnwin32/your-first-windows-program) to make a Win32 window then passed the handle to SFML and noticed on 3.0.0 the window is totally unresponsive. When debugging I see we get trapped infinitely processing GL errors. Whereas on 2.6.2 we process a single error then report that. 

I presume a default Qt app redirects the stdout or is just a Win32 app so you can't see the stdout easily, that means you would never see the stream of GL errors being shouted by SFML. I also tried this by using glfw to create a window then passing the handle to SFML and get the same result. I have no clue _why_ this is happening but this is my leading theory. If someone wants to install Qt and verify this be my guest, but the fact the below example works fine with 2.6.2 but not 3.0.0 leads me to believe this might be the issue you're experiencing.

```cpp
#include <GLFW/glfw3.h>
#define GLFW_EXPOSE_NATIVE_WIN32
#include <GLFW/glfw3native.h>

int main(void)
{
    GLFWwindow* window;

    /* Initialize the library */
    if (!glfwInit())
        return -1;

    /* Create a windowed mode window and its OpenGL context */
    window = glfwCreateWindow(640, 480, "Hello World", NULL, NULL);
    if (!window)
    {
        glfwTerminate();
        return -1;
    }

    sf::RenderWindow wind (glfwGetWin32Window(window));
    
    /* Make the window's context current */
    glfwMakeContextCurrent(window);

    /* Loop until the user closes the window */
    while (!glfwWindowShouldClose(window))
    {
        /* Render here */
        glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

        /* Swap front and back buffers */
        glfwSwapBuffers(window);

        /* Poll for and process events */
        glfwPollEvents();
    }

    glfwTerminate();
    return 0;
}
```

The errors being constantly spat out on 3.0.0 were
```
An internal OpenGL call failed in "RenderWindow.cpp"(113).
Expression:
   glGetIntegerv(GLEXT_GL_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING, reinterpret_cast<GLint*>(&m_defaultFrameBuffer))
Error description:
   GL_INVALID_OPERATION
   The specified operation is not allowed in the current state.
```

on 2.6.2 I get this singular output:
```
An internal OpenGL call failed in RenderWindow.cpp(125).
Expression:
   glGetIntegerv(GLEXT_GL_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING, reinterpret_cast<GLint*>(&m_defaultFrameBuffer))
Error description:
   GL_INVALID_OPERATION
   The specified operation is not allowed in the current state.

Failed to set pixel format for device context: The pixel format is invalid.
Cannot create OpenGL context
```

@Wolfmyths if you attach a debugger and pause it during the unresponsiveness, you can confirm my findings by telling us if the debugger halts within SFML's code for processing GL errors (`glCheckError` function in SFML).
